      <pubtit>Genomic analyses provide insights into spinach domestication and the genetic basis of agronomic traits</pubtit>
      <p><img src="http://localhost:4000/images/pubpic/spinach.jpg" class="img-responsive" width="33%" style="float: left" /></p>
      <p>Most of us are familiar with "spinach teeth" ‚Äì the harmless but gritty-chalky mouthfeel caused by the vegetable. An international team led by us has identified genes in spinach that regulate its concentration of oxalate, which is responsible for "spinach teeth", as well as genes that help the plant combat downy mildew, a major disease of commercial crops.</p>
      <p><em>X Cai<sup>#</sup>, <strong><u>X Sun</u><sup>#</sup></strong>, C Xu<sup>#</sup>, H Sun, X Wang, C Ge, Z Zhang, Q Wang<sup>*</sup>, Z Fei<sup>*</sup>, C Jiao<sup>*#</sup>, Q Wang<sup>*</sup>.</em></p>
      <p><strong><a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-021-27432-z">Nature Communications 12:7246 (2021)</a></strong></p>
      <p class="text-danger"><strong> </strong></p>
      <p> see <a href="https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2021/12/gene-discoveries-could-lead-heartier-less-gritty-spinach">Cornell Chronicle</a>, <a href="https://www.zju.edu.cn/english/2021/1222/c19573a2453904/page.htm">ZJU News</a>, <a href="http://www.cab.zju.edu.cn/chinese/2021/1215/c11148a2451673/page.htm">‰∏≠ÊñáÊä•ÈÅì</a></p>
